3-2-2-4l-1-3-1%202-1%204-2%206-1%205h-4c-4-1-6-2-4-4%201%200%202%200%203%202%201%201%201%201%201-3%200-3%200-4%202-4%202-1%202-1-1-1l-3%201v2l-1-2-21-1-20-1%206-2h2c0-1-4-2-6-1l-3%202c0%202-1%202-6%202l-5-1v-3c-1-1-1-1-1%201s-1%203-2%203a2073%202073%200%200%200-14%200l-2-10-1-8%201%208m227%2010h-15l1%204c0%204%202%205%202%201v-4h31a1100%201100%200%200%200-19-1m-212%202%201%201v2l-4%201h-3l-2%201v-1l1-3-2%201-3%205c0%202%201%202%2023%202h23v-5l-1-5-1%203-1%201-1-2c0-2-1-2-3-2-4%200-4%200-4%203l1%202%201%201c-2%202-3%201-3-2s-1-4-3-4l-3%201c0%201%201%202%202%201l1%201-4%203-1-5h-3c-5%201-5%201-3%203l3%202h-3l-3-1-1-2-1-2-1-1-2%201m40%201h-2l-2-1%201%202v1l-1%203-1%203h8a815%20815%200%200%200%2011-2c-1-1%200-2%201-3v-2l-1%201-4%201c-1-1-1-1%201-2v-1l-2-1c0-2-9-1-9%201'%20fill='%23d3d3d3'%20fill-rule='evenodd'/%3e%3c/svg%3e"},"images":{"fallback":{"src":"/static/2e742d6ab1be3dba7f759067d1353ef2/bc51f/image.png","srcSet":"/static/2e742d6ab1be3dba7f759067d1353ef2/41200/image.png 165w,\n/static/2e742d6ab1be3dba7f759067d1353ef2/f979a/image.png 330w,\n/static/2e742d6ab1be3dba7f759067d1353ef2/bc51f/image.png 660w,\n/static/2e742d6ab1be3dba7f759067d1353ef2/f57dd/image.png 1320w","sizes":"(min-width: 660px) 660px, 100vw"},"sources":[{"srcSet":"/static/2e742d6ab1be3dba7f759067d1353ef2/322ad/image.webp 165w,\n/static/2e742d6ab1be3dba7f759067d1353ef2/de3b3/image.webp 330w,\n/static/2e742d6ab1be3dba7f759067d1353ef2/2b2b5/image.webp 660w,\n/static/2e742d6ab1be3dba7f759067d1353ef2/e36a7/image.webp 1320w","type":"image/webp","sizes":"(min-width: 660px) 660px, 100vw"}]},"width":660,"height":400}}}},"body":"<h1>An Ideal Classroom</h1>\n<p>Schiro (2013) points out that it has been incredibly difficult for agreement to be reached regarding curriculum “The competition between the four visions of education has also made it difficult for educators and the general public to reach a consensus” (p.1). I found as I was reading that it was challenging for me to decide unequivocally what my curriculum ideology was or is.</p>\n<p>At first, I was certain that I was team Learner Centered. This ideology appeals to me on many levels as an inquiry, skills, and concepts-based teacher. The idea that as Shiro (2020) purports that there should be joy that comes from learning. Schools are meant to be places where “harmony” can be found according to one’s own individual social, emotional, and intellectual growth. Where the student remains at the center of it all. This is reflected in what the International Baccalaureate espouses “An IB education is holistic in nature—it is concerned with the whole person. Along with cognitive development, IB programmes address students’ social, emotional and physical well-being” (p. 8). At the same time, there are aspects of Social Efficiency Ideology that appeal to me. For example, the idea that we are preparing our students for life outside of school. This philosophy is reminiscent of this idea that we are working to equip our students with the skills need to be successful for the 21st century. How many times have we heard this adage “We are currently preparing students for jobs and technologies that don’t yet exist… in order to solve problems that we don’t even know are problems yet” (YouTube 2021). Finally, I was also drawn to The Social Reconstruction Ideology for its commitment to educating our students to want to make the world a better place. Social reconstruction offers hope for a better future though the education of our students. There is no denying that we live in a world in crisis (unfortunately). Erickson (2011) points out that we live in a world that has moved from national to global. We have problems that need solving on an international level from environmental, climate change, immigration and emigration, conflicts with no resolutions, health problems, the list continues to grow. The skills that may have been required in the past are almost no longer applicable in today’s globalized world.What better way than to educate our future change makers and innovators than in school?</p>\n<p>My classroom drawing represents what I wish education looked like- a little bit messy but with some method behind my madness. This is “blue- sky thinking” at its finest. It is a middle school classroom for grades 6-8. Ideally there would be 16-18 students. The most important to me is the idea of outdoor space. I once worked at a school on 11 acres, with hills for sledding on in the winter, bird banding, doors that opened to the field, an outdoor classroom and two massive fields for running and playing. It made learning exciting for both me and the students. I am a firm believer that as Sobel points out “If we want children to flourish, to become truly empowered, let us allow them to love the earth before we ask them to save it.” I included gardens, farm animals, and water where the experiential learning can take place. Inside, there are many windows- for transparency, doors, that open to the outside and a LOT of room. Desks are standing or sitting, moveable and there are tables for collaboration. Included are workstations for projects with a view outside for dreaming. Reading areas and comfortable areas to do your work are scattered throughout the room. My design is based on a comfortable coffee shop you might like to go to do your work. There are charging stations around the room and at strategic spots on the floor. An interactive white board is included for presentations and for music. As you will not there is no teacher desk. This model signifies that the learning is happening all around us, both students and teachers are learning together. It is my feeling that this is a student-centered classroom. The environment including the outdoors provides a lot of scope for the learner to make meaning from the world around them.</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://slideplayer.com/slide/2296648/\">Erickson, L. (2015). Concept-based unit design according to Dr. Lynn Erickson. [PowerPoint slides]. Slideshare</a></p>\n<p><a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fbcMPGyPr8k\">Esteves, J. (2021). Did you know 2021 [Video]. YouTube. </a></p>\n<p>Schiro M.S. (2013). Curriculum theory: Conflicting visions and enduring concerns (2nd ed.). SAGE Publications.</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://magazine.communityworksinstitute.org/beyond-ecophobia-reclaiming-the-heart-in-nature-education/\">Sobel, D. (2019). Beyond Ecophobia: Reclaiming the Heart in Nature Education. Community Works Journal.</a></p>\n<p><a href=\"https://dpi.wi.gov/sites/default/files/imce/cal/pdf/what-is-an-ib-education.pdf\">What is an IB education? (n.d.).</a></p>","categories":["Personal Project","MYP"],"date":"October 19, 2022","description":"Schiro (2013) points out that it has been incredibly difficult for agreement to be reached regarding curriculum “The competition between the four visions of education has also made it difficult for educators and the general public to reach a consensus” (p.1). I found as I was reading that it was challenging for me to decide unequivocally what my curriculum ideology was or is.","id":"8fc9ac08-e69c-5665-a7ec-6e294ffb09ad","keywords":["experiential","education","blog"],"slug":"/an-ideal-classroom/","title":"An Ideal Classroom","readingTime":{"text":"4 min read"}},"listingPagePath":"/blog"}},"staticQueryHashes":["1094019748","4239582004"]}